A Czech arbitrator fights for the seabed
It approaches a wall electronic map, on which Australia and adjacent marine areas are represented.
Now, he is not interested in the continent, but in a little lost spot in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia, as does the adjacent seabed.
Yet this area is as big as the continent itself," said Italian lawyer Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the team of thirty members of the UN Division for Ocean Affairs and the Law of the Sea.
Its head, the director of the division, the Czech lawyer Václav Mikulka, follows the presentation and completes it from time to time.
Ardor at work and enthusiasm characterize the prevailing atmosphere.
The seabed hides a world so far little known, rich in natural resources.
Oil, minerals and other mineral resources can be found there, but also living organisms currently unknown, which may contain the key to the development of a cancer drug.
A wider background than the solid earth
Today, coastal states have begun to aspire vehemently to new underwater territories.
According to a UN convention, they are indeed exercising their rights, which they agreed on in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
According to the convention, the latter can claim exclusively all the resources of the continental shelf.
To simplify, the continental shelf is considered the part of the seabed and its subsoil, which constitutes a natural extension of the continent under the sea.
It extends beyond the borders of the coastal sea, often also beyond the two hundred nautical miles that represent the exclusive economic yone," explains Mikulka.
The request that the country in question submits to the Commission for the establishment of the outer borders of the continental shelf must be supported by extensive scientific and technical documentation, based on many costly surveys and metrics.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the commission with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
To date, the Commission has dealt with five requests, including those from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
At the moment, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful," adds Mikulka.
Australia's success, which is the first to have significantly expanded its underwater possessions, has recently experienced a global impact.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed, which was assigned to it by the commission last week, corresponds to 1.6 million square kilometers, which is the extent of the country multiplied by six.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The benefits they will derive from the future exploitation of the seabed will, as they project, be invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will, in turn, submit their request.
They can do so within ten years of ratifying the Montego Bay Convention.
There, where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of humanity".
There is no longer any state that enjoys an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this area is granted by an international institution established by convention.
"However, let us not be mistaken, the seabed is not a Klondike," said Director Mikulka, adding that "its areas are clearly defined and their regime is anchored in a contract."
Czechs in the Pacific
A part of the seabed is now also owned by the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other former Eastern bloc states within the framework of the joint organization "Interoceanmetal".
In 1991, under the Convention, as well as investors from a few other States, it obtained the status of a so-called "pioneer investor".
It has the right of extraction in the ClarionClipperton area in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
The area prospected by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The bottom is agitated, it is a kind of underwater replica of the Tatra.
"It is possible to extract on an area with a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area represents a polymetallic concrete deposit rich in nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese," says Ind Pakshi Rajan, another lawyer.
Rober Sandev, a Macedonian employee of the division, provides an example of such concreteness.
It resembles a small potato, or, with a little imagination, the mythical shoem, which, according to legend, animated the Golem.
