Organizers report increasing number of bookings
This should be a good winter for German travel agencies:
In terms of bookings for the coming months, according to a study, turnover has increased significantly compared to the previous year - for the winter season, even by more than 30 percent.
Despite the weak economic outlook, the Germans’ travel thirst remains insatiable, according to this study.
As for bookings for the winter season, travel agencies recorded sales of more than 31 percent compared to the same period the previous year, as entrusted to Berlin on Monday by the German Federation of Travel Agencies (DRV).
According to the survey of the GfK Market Research Institute, increasing numbers of bookings already dominate the autumn months.
Thus, the sales figure would have climbed to about 11 percent more than in 2007, the DRV said.
The sources of these results are figures from the GfK, which analyses booking data from 1,200 travel agencies monthly and makes estimates for the global market.
Travel bookings made since the end of August 2008 would be recorded there.
Due to the low dollar exchange rate, travel to the US would be particularly in demand, the DRV said.
There, the increase in bookings would amount to about one-third.
In addition to this, Spain, Turkey and Greece, as well as our country, would be destinations particularly sought after by the Germans.
Particularly organized trips are in high demand, explained DRV President Klaus Laepple.
In view of rising energy and food prices, the costs here would be "easier for the customer to calculate than for an individually organized trip".
Consumers can save money, among other things, with early booking discounts or All Inclusive offers, Laepple explained.
The summer months have also been very successful so that an increase in sales figures will again be recorded compared to last year - although according to another study, the number of Germans who have undertaken a trip has fallen compared to the previous year.
