Turkey is expanding its diplomatic horizons.
Long before Turkey thought of joining the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate its hinterland.
On the east side of the Bosphorus, 20 steps may be, from Asia, lies one of the finest relics of its fallen imperial ambition.
Hydarpasha railway station was designed in a neo-Renaissance style by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu.
At least that’s what the guides tell us.
The monument is arranged on horseback at the bottom of the platforms, equipped with observation towers at each of its angles, like some German provincial town halls.
The stones are dirty.
The whole building is in ruins.
But once inside the vaulted ticket office, we no longer have any doubts about the size of the company, which represents a passage to the west.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by a German association, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Lagging behind in the game of imperialism, Germany wanted to realize its medieval ambitions of domination thanks to this railway that reaches Damascus, Baghdad as well as the most famous land known as Saudi Arabia.
But German imperialist ambitions collapsed during the First World War.
Its railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregulars.
The relative isolation of its surrounding region, engendered by the icy borders of the Cold War, is over.
. The British and Empire forces advanced beyond Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
But there was also bad news for Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, a train loaded with ammunition exploded destroying its subtle roof.
According to Turkish sources, this was sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly fallen into ruin, engulfed in the meanders of history.
But today, the railway crossing to Anatolia and all the eastern points serves, at least symbolically, to underline Turkey's widening diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development party, the AKP, has created a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of its surrounding region, caused by the icy borders of the Cold War
Now is the time for a new policy of commitments.
The Turkish government has remarkable relations with Israel and Syria, the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, Iran and Iraq, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To judge the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded a bedding wagon towards the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit Turkish AKP MP Suat Kiniklioglu, one of the foreign policy experts.
The next morning, after a 10-and-a-half-hour journey, shaking on noisy rails whose cadence reminded the old world of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I finally arrived in the Turkish capital – presented as a new city of a new secular state, turning my back on its German past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamist roots is an example of changing the Turkish consensus.
He suspected the West, and especially Washington.
A taxi accompanied me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern structure, expressly built of stones and steel, in a developing district, surrounded by half-built shopping centers and many pastry shops in which the middle managers in suit-tie-men and women- meet for business in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu could have been a centre-right politician from any other party in Europe.
Costume, tie and he even has a Black Berry.
"The purpose of this foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he said.
Turkey has been cut off from its back country.
Now she must look east and west at the same time.
This was not the case for both of them.
She had to do both.
“But at some point, I asked if ‘Turkey shouldn’t choose’.
"Turkey," he said, "doesn't want to have to choose between the two."
He then pointed out an aspect that almost everyone I was able to talk to has recited to me from the heart: the Turkish railway not only goes to the Middle East, but also to the Caucasus, and around the Black Sea, so it is as much an advantage for Europe and the United States as for Turkey itself.
With the integration of Turkey, the message seems to draw a Europe traveling metaphorically on the rails towards Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha station, after another night without sleep, I thought back to those two Germans, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who followed the construction of this building 100 years ago.
They would have been surprised to see that the European ambitions of the Middle East could, in large part, be in the hands of Turkey.
As I waited at the terminal, the ferry to cross the Bosphorus, I remembered the period when Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe".
At least, there is no longer any doubt on the continent that could claim this fascinating country.
