William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary of William Woodruff (died 25 September) states that "in 1946 he resumed his studies in economic history at Oxford, and in 1950 became a member of Houblon-Norma research, while doing a BSc, an MA and a PhD."
That's what comes from Woodruff's letter in Beyond Nab End, but that's not correct.
From 1946 to 1953 he was Professor of Economic History at the University of Nottingham, and at the same time completed a PhD thesis on the British plastics industry, under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers; it was then published in 1958 under the title The British Rubber Industry.
In the 1950s and 51s in the United States, he studied at the Norman Houblon, and in the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard, and New York.
In 1953, he left Nottingham for Illinois.
The reason why Woodruff chose to conceal this part of his past remains unknown.
