Morgan Stanley said the overall transaction would be based on an average unit price of $29, 28% above its current price.
The Morgan Stanley share, however, lost 6.79% at $23.07 around 5pm GMT.
“This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to bank holding status,” said John Mack, the group’s CEO.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new status last week, which should allow him to diversify his activities but pass it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street’s biggest names to adopt a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented on Monday also show that the deal has been modified over the past few days: on Monday, Morgan had simply announced that he would sell up to 20% of his shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
"A week ago, Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, told Tokyo, we thought that participation would be entirely composed of ordinary shares.
But given the current situation of the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves."
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the transaction will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferential securities into ordinary shares in a year if the latter trade more than 50% above the conversion price, or about $47, for a given period.
Morgan Stanley says MUFG’s capital will enable it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
However, a spokeswoman for the group declined to provide details on the strategic projects of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to display a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the sector.
Morgan said he had "cleanly" eased his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been challenging for the group, which saw its stock market price melt by half as the cost of insurance against a risk of default on its debt flew up.
The cost declined on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
