Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, he was the third to put forward a draft of a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to official results with 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" scored 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to get half the vote plus one.
On Sunday, two polls carried out at the polling stations and a count of a non-governmental organization had announced a broad victory of the "yes", standing between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed the victory of his draft constitution on Sunday night.
The "Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly," he said, congratulating Ecuadorians at the Guayaquil Governorate headquarters, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place quietly according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), was about a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution consecrates the power of the state over the economy, reserving to it the "development planning" of a country that lives mainly from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currencies sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also gives the head of state enhanced powers, which will be able to serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and contest a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad.
An Egyptian commando launched an assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were returned safely to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived around 3:30 p.m. aboard a special plane at al-Maza military base, which is docked at Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, unable to speak to the press, on helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examinations.
They are "in good health" and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the tarmac.
Captured on 19 September during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been swept from one hide-and-seek by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Egyptian agency, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, dispatched on board two helicopters, had launched the assault on the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of shots took place, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fleeing," said the official, who requested anonymity.
He said that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit had been sent to Sudan in total, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of the Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is located, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our intelligence and special forces men," he said.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on board a patrol, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army had claimed they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement had immediately denied.
Letters - The Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes headlines and occupies the current election campaign.
It's so much better.
But one aspect of our cultural life is still forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the sums of misery granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical sites that are starving?
What politician would dare to remind the federal government that it neglects its monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we don't have real laws that actually preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government is devoting three and a half million euros to the restoration of the only Château de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
In our American neighbors, it is written in the Constitution of their country that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all elected and all government departments, and this, in concert.
In Quebec, at the Fédération des Sociétés d'Histoire du Québec, at least 40,000 volunteers grouped in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned about digging history, preserving with three under private archives and preserving archaeological collections.
They are often the watchdogs of our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when promoters and decision makers launch their bulldozers against our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When, a tribune for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis Bank
As the first European banking institution in distress as a result of the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, the Benelux states partially nationalize the bank, which is also supported by a sum of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion in insurance, this financial institution is also able to provide financial assistance.
