A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about his/her drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that bind the use of information regarding the prescription of medicines, in any case, to the consent of the data subject.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is about entrusting its henhouse to a fox," Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the premium and capital insured in the event of damage depend on the health status of the client, and if they feel that the risk is too high, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent candidates for a medical examination, and they only signed an insurance contract with them after they learned of the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a procedure much cheaper: from an identification number, it is easily provided from pharmacies, data on the purchases of drugs of the person within the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, what disease the person suffers from and what is his health condition.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol lowering, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which puts him immediately in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk factor, so there is not much more to do for the insurer other than paperwork. However, tiny problems can still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes, for example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data. They must ask for the patient's permission before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are being forced by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their past failures.
Recently, some companies have also been processing laboratory analysis results and linking them to drug consumption data, enabling them to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and usage control is becoming increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill on expanding the authority's control of companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not sufficient and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive consent of the person concerned.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he or she refuses, insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
Thus and in the end, the chickens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other largely global problems.
Today, there will also be a France-India summit where cooperation in the field of nuclear energy will be discussed.
The European Union recognizes that India is a large emerging democratic power that should be given a broader voice in international affairs, but the member countries have not yet been able to agree on their support in New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They were not too late on this issue yesterday at this 9th summit held in Marseille.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, as the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the head of diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Prime Minister of India, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years, they would double the trade of centavos, which means one billion.
Bearing in mind that between 2000 and 2007, the trade in goods rose from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be an overly ambitious goal.
In this sense, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral conventions with India on civil flights, so that air traffic can also take off in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with, on the one hand, India, which is the EU's first trading partner, and on the other, New Delhi, which is only in ninth place among the EU's partners.
The summit focused its attention on global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan has been strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a UN conference on this issue has been mentioned.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been requested, although both have a large part in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains faithful to the energy and climate programme, notably that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic substances by at least 20 percent by 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as with the fact that a comprehensive market would need to be passed at the climate conference scheduled next year, and reduce greenhouse gas emissions by fifty percent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent food prices from rising, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The head of state of India is visiting the French capital, where he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth twenty billion euros for the construction of Indian nuclear reactors.
According to the press agency, the agreement would be for 15 years.
