Found Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire missing a year ago.
The wreckage of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris was found on a 3,000-metre high plateau in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson said: “The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that it is indeed the one Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared,” he said at a press conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found either on the plane or in the vicinity.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Bureau of Transportation Safety (NTSB) said a few hours after the wreckage was spotted, a team of investigators sent to the site identified the device: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, missing on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some personal belongings from Fosset were found by a couple around their Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents bearing the name Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's research was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
At the sixth attempt, he had become in 2002, the first man to complete the world tour on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had travelled around the world by plane and without a stopover.
Among all these records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters high, over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
